defaultHow should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?
defaultThe governance of the BBC remains a live issue for politics and regulation per se.
defaultMoreover, it is clear that the UK is moving towards an ever more federal-like polity with the Parliament in Edinburgh and Assemblies in Cardiff and Belfast having legitimate expectations of 
default–
defaultat the very least- having an appropriate level of involvement in the accountability processes which the BBC 
default–
defaultand (not incidentally) Channel 4, S4C, 
defaultthe
default Gaelic Media Service and not least OFCOM are required to meet.
default&#xa0;
defaultBroadcasting should no longer be a power reserved to Westminster.defaultTheredefault should be an amendment to the Scotland Act 1998 to allow for the BBC to have a measure of formal accountability to the Scottish Parliament, with the annual report of BBC Scotland presented  to the Parliament and subject to scrutiny and debate although Minister of the Scottish Government (or indeed the UK government) should be held accountable or presume to be responsible for the decisions and policies of what is an independent corporate body. defaultGiven the fact that the BBC World Service is now funded out of the licence fee and the profits of BBC Worldwide- the time has also come for the decisions on the provdefaultision of content in other languadefaultges etc to be a matter for the BBC and its governing body- advised rather than set by the UK government.defaultIn a constantly evolving communications environment, does a 10-year Royal Charter and Agreement with the Secretary of State, together, provide the most appropriate constitutional framework for the BBC?
defaultThere is a strong case for establishing the BBC Charter on a permanent rather than a ten year basis. defaultIt is impossible to imagine a UK without the BBC. Universities have Royal Charters which operate for centuries. Therefore we must ask why the BBC Charter is given only for ten years.defaultThe answer would that the changing nature of technology and society and culture requires this kind of scrutiny at pre-determined intervals. But what is also clear is that opening up the debate every ten years leads to repeated arguments around the scale, scope and existence of the BBC with the many enemies of the Corporation attempting yet again to have the BBC privatised or diminished, in each case for their own ideological and/or economic interests.
defaultI have never forgotten attending one of the Burns seminars in 2005 when a participant attempted to open up the question of the very existence of the BBC as well as the licence fee and had to be told by Lord Burns that a previous seminar in the series had already addressed this issue. 
defaultThe central point isdefault that from 1926 until 2006, under the pdefaultrevious governance structure default–default ie the defaultBBC Governors, the BdefaultBC succeeded defaultin meeting the challenges of the enormous changes in technology- from wireless to television to the internet- in society and culture and taking into adefaultccount the many political pressures applied to it.defaultThe governors were both default–default in modern parlance- regulators and cheerleaders default–default but they succeeded in bringing us the BBC which existed in 2006. Despite the political claims that the current BBC Trust is broken- and the problems of Savile etc, and the variable performance of BBC Trust officials at Westminster, it is not clear or proven that the Trust needs to be abolished rather than reformed.default&#xa0;defaultI should be happy to provide further ideas on this and other matters should the committee wish to call me to give evidence.defaultNovember 2013
